
A robust anti-corruption system—especially for a global
democratic compact like the Earth Compact—must go beyond
enforcement and address structure, incentives, transparency,
and culture. Here’s a comprehensive, multi-tiered
Anti-Corruption System, designed to align with the Compact’s
democratic, leaderless, and citizen-centered ethos:

🌐
--

Anti-Corruption Framework for the Earth Compact1. Structural
Separation of Powers + Redundancy

Multilayered Oversight: Create separate, independently elected
or randomly selected bodies for:

Budget oversight

Ethics investigations

Procurement auditing

No concentration of financial, legislative, and judicial
authority in any single body (e.g., no unchecked executive).

✅ Inspired by: Swiss cantonal checks, US Inspector General
model, and EU Court of Auditors

2. Citizens’ Integrity Chamber (CIC)

A rotating body of citizen-jurors, selected by lottery,
demographically representative, and tasked with:

Reviewing high-level decisions

Hearing whistleblower cases

Approving exceptions to standard procedures

Members serve short, non-renewable terms to avoid entrenchment.

✅ Inspired by: Citizen juries, Ireland’s Citizens' Assembly,
Sortition theory

3. Radical Transparency + Public Ledger

Mandatory publication of:

All public contracts and budgets

Meeting minutes of all decision-making bodies

Lobbying interactions and donations

Immutable open-source ledgers (blockchain or cryptographic logs)
track:

Asset declarations of officials

Public spending

AI or algorithmic decision logs

✅ Inspired by: Estonia’s digital transparency system, Open
Contracting Partnership, Git transparency models

4. Whistleblower Protection + Anonymous Reporting

Global, end-to-end encrypted anonymous channels for reporting
corruption.

Legal immunity and financial reward for verified whistleblowers.

Retaliation equals automatic ethics investigation of superior.

✅ Inspired by: SEC whistleblower program, Transparency
International models

5. AI & Algorithmic Oversight

AI used not only to flag anomalies in procurement, budgeting,
and asset declarations—but its code and training data must be:

Open source

Auditable by civil society

An independent AI Ethics Ombudsman monitors misuse.

✅ Inspired by: Brazil’s AI-powered audit tools, open-source
principles

6. Decentralized Investigative Media Grants

Fund and protect independent, cross-border investigative
journalism through:

Firewalled funding pools from Compact Partners

Rotating editorial oversight by civil society boards

Incentivize collaborations between media, data scientists, and
civic coders.

✅ Inspired by: OCCRP, ProPublica, and the Panama Papers model

7. Ethics Veto + Popular Impeachment

Any citizen (or group) may submit a formal petition for:

Ethics veto of a pending decision

Popular impeachment vote of a public official

Trigger thresholds require only a fixed percentage of verified
citizen support, not elite approval.

✅ Inspired by: Swiss Referenda + recall systems

8. Civic Education + Integrity Culture

Mandatory integrity and civic ethics training for all public
servants, with:

Open-source curriculum

Citizen-evaluated performance reviews

Anti-corruption values embedded in education, media, and public
rituals.

✅ Inspired by: Singapore’s anti-corruption campaigns and
Finnish civic education

9. Independent Global Anti-Corruption Tribunal

Permanent international tribunal with jurisdiction over:

Cross-border corruption

Compact signatory officials

Cases may be initiated by:

Member states

Ethics Commissions

Civil society bodies

✅ Inspired by: International Criminal Court + World Bank
Sanctions Board

10. Transparent Enforcement & Sanctions Matrix

Sanctions for corruption (bribery, embezzlement, abuse of power)
include:

Loss of office

Public censure

Personal financial restitution

Bar from future public service

Sanctions applied openly, with full due process, and documented
in public archives.

